=========================================
C++ unordered_multiset – Interview Notes
=========================================

1. What is unordered_multiset?
------------------------------
unordered_multiset is an unordered associative container that stores duplicate values.

Implemented using:
- Hash Table

Header:
#include <unordered_set>

Syntax:
unordered_multiset<int> ums;

----------------------------------------

2. Properties
-------------
✓ Stores only values (no key-value pair)
✓ Duplicate values are allowed
✓ No ordering of elements
✓ Average O(1) insertion/search/deletion
✓ Worst case O(n) (hash collisions)
✓ Elements are stored according to hash buckets

----------------------------------------

3. Example
----------

#include <iostream>
#include <unordered_set>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    unordered_multiset<int> ums;

    ums.insert(10);
    ums.insert(20);
    ums.insert(10);
    ums.insert(30);
    ums.insert(20);

    for(auto x : ums)
        cout << x << " ";
}

Possible Output:
20 10 30 20 10

(Output order is NOT guaranteed.)

----------------------------------------

4. Common Functions
-------------------

insert()

ums.insert(10);

erase(value)

ums.erase(10);

Removes ALL occurrences of 10.

erase(iterator)

auto it = ums.find(10);
if(it != ums.end())
    ums.erase(it);

Removes only one occurrence.

find()

auto it = ums.find(20);

Returns iterator to one occurrence.

count()

cout << ums.count(10);

Returns number of occurrences.

size()

ums.size();

empty()

ums.empty();

clear()

ums.clear();

equal_range()

auto range = ums.equal_range(10);

Returns iterators to all occurrences.

----------------------------------------

5. Iteration
------------

for(auto x : ums)
    cout << x << " ";

OR

for(auto it = ums.begin(); it != ums.end(); ++it)
    cout << *it << " ";

----------------------------------------

6. Time Complexity
------------------

Insert      O(1) average
Find        O(1) average
Erase       O(1) average
Count       O(1) average

Worst Case:
O(n)

----------------------------------------

7. unordered_set vs unordered_multiset
--------------------------------------

unordered_set
--------------
Duplicates NOT allowed

unordered_multiset
------------------
Duplicates allowed

Both:
- Hash Table
- Unordered
- Average O(1)

----------------------------------------

8. multiset vs unordered_multiset
---------------------------------

multiset
---------
Balanced BST (Red-Black Tree)
Sorted
O(log n)

unordered_multiset
------------------
Hash Table
Not Sorted
Average O(1)

----------------------------------------

9. Important Interview Questions
--------------------------------

Q1. Can unordered_multiset store duplicates?
Yes.

Q2. Is data sorted?
No.

Q3. Which data structure is used internally?
Hash Table.

Q4. Can we use lower_bound()?
No.
Works only for ordered containers.

Q5. How do we count duplicates?

ums.count(value);

Q6. How to remove only one duplicate?

auto it = ums.find(value);
if(it != ums.end())
    ums.erase(it);

Q7. How to remove all duplicates?

ums.erase(value);

----------------------------------------

10. When to Use?
----------------

Use unordered_multiset when:
✓ Duplicate values are needed.
✓ Order doesn't matter.
✓ Fast insertion/search/deletion is required.

Examples:
- Frequency tracking with duplicate storage
- Counting repeated values
- Fast duplicate lookups

